  "text": "below 5 x 105 spores/ml., encystment in the dark approached the high level obtained in light, hence a light effect was not observed. Population density was therefore a critical factor for encystment in the dark; if this relationship was a consequence of 'self inhibition' [CITATION_1] )~ visible light may have been functioning, in part at least, by overcoming its influence. It may be significant that in the media used by Soll & Sonneborn (1969)~ not tested in the present study, germination synchrony was independent of spore concentration up to 4-2 x 105 cells/ml., whereas above 5.9 x 105 cellslml., population density exerted inhibitory effects. Light-induced encystment ceased abruptly when spores were transferred to darkness (Fig. 2) . Attempts were made with filters to ascertain which regions of the visible spectrum were the most effective for inducing encystment. Preliminary results suggested that blue light (400 to 500 nm.) was effective, but other wavelengths also seemed to play a role.",
